    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>May 3d 1872<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Ma&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/>
            My Dear Sir.<lb/></p>
            <p>Mrs. Maney<lb/> of New York has called<lb/> my attention to the book&#44;<lb/> as per the within title&#44;<lb/> which she claims would<lb/> be a <sic>valuble</sic> book for<lb/> publication by the &#34;Jew&#45;<lb/>ish Publication Society&#44;&#34;<lb/> and for that purpose<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p> would translate it.  She<lb/> thinks you know the<lb/> author personally and<lb/> I have no doubt<lb/> you are familiar<lb/> with the work.<lb/></p>
            <p>I give the &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/>tion&#44; as given to me&#44;<lb/> for whatever it is<lb/> worth.<lb/>
            Permit me to<lb/> avail of this occasion<lb/> to express my deeply<lb/></p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>felt sympathy for<lb/> you and yours in the<lb/> great loss you have<lb/> sustained by the<lb/> death of Mrs. Maurice<lb/>&#45;&#45;a lady respected<lb/> and beloved wherever<lb/> known.<lb/></p>
            <p>Although it was<lb/> not my privilege to<lb/> meet her of late years<lb/> I always recur to<lb/> my early associations<lb/> with her as one of<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>the most delightful<lb/> periods of my life.<lb/>
            With regards<lb/>
            I am<lb/>
            yours truly<lb/>
            A. J. Solomons<lb/></p>

        </body>
    </text>
